The technological pathway to whole brain emulation

speaker: Ed Boyden

Foresight Institute Neurotechnology Workshop 2025

video: <https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q5HSZDlJ16c&list=PLH78wfbGI1x0bxPV95uWxH-8G3DmLDBeX&index=1>

LLM summary: Ed Boyden presents a vision for achieving [[whole brain emulation|brain emulation]] through integrated [[neurotechnologies|brain-computer interfaces]] that enable high-fidelity mapping, imaging, and control of brain dynamics at cellular and molecular scales, drawing analogies to physics' "ground truth" of fundamental particles enabling bottom-up engineering like microchips; he highlights scaling [[optogenetics]] via holographic projection for real-time control of every neuron in small brains (e.g., fish, worms), ultrafast light-sheet voltage imaging at 200 volumes/second in larval zebrafish using advanced indicators and remote refocusing to reveal microscope limitations over indicator blame, and [[expansion microscopy]] enhancements including multiplexed 20-nm resolution antibody imaging of mouse cortex synapses, controlled protein fragmentation for single-molecule structural mapping matching crystallography or ML predictions, and parallels to genome expansion-sequencing; these tools converge to generate connectomic-molecular maps supporting top-down network predictions, mechanism inference from dynamics, and purely bottom-up simulations for therapeutics, philosophy, and AI, with emerging prospects like index-matching for **transparent living mammalian brains**.


